<TITLE> AL observing historic 'Six-point Day' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 7 (bdnews24.com)The historic 'Six-point Day' is being observed Sunday by ruling Awami League which led the country to independence from Pakistan in 1971. On Feb 5, 1966 in Lahore, AL leader Sheikh Mujibur Rahman had introduced the six-point charter of demands of the Bengalis, which included the demand of autonomy of East Pakistan through establishment of a federal government. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina along with the AL presidium members, cabinet members, MPs and other leaders and workers placed wreaths at Sheikh Mujib's portrait at Bangabandhu Smrity Jadughar or memorial museum. The national flag and AL flag were also hoisted atop AL central office on Bangabandhu Avenue in the morning. On June 7, 1966, the AL had enforced a hartal call across East Pakistan demanding the realisation of its six-point demands, the Bangalees' charter of freedom. During the hartal that day, Monu Mia, Shafiq, Shamsul Haq and a number of other pickets were shot and killed by the Pakistani army in Dhaka, Narayanganj and Tongi. "Following the path beaten by the vanguards and the exponents of the 'six-point movement', the Bangalees won their freedom in 1971," Tofail Ahmed, senior AL leader, told reporters in the morning "June 7 thus carries a glorious memorial burden for the nation." The AL will hold a discussion meeting at 4pm in Bangladesh-China Friendship Conference Centre chaired over by Hasina, the AL chief
